title: DevOps Starter - Make GitHubActions the default
Organisation templates for Azure (experiment)

comments.body: Solution from Usha available - https://github.com/Azure/actions-workflow-samples/tree/workflow-templates

Some comments or thoughts:
1) It is awesome to see that the instructions are simple - fork the repo and rename it as .github public repo. If a customer does this it will add >20 templates to their repo - will spoil their experience. Any thoughts? Keep only P0 templates or organize with resource/language pivot so they can delete the directories that are not needed.
2) If you have folder structure and an organization copies it, does it show all templates in flat structure or organize them? If it is organizing in folders it probably helps solving #1 and makes it easier as well.
3) Should we be calling this as azure\action-workflow-templates  as these are templates than samples.

Assuming this work is in progress, few more to be fixed: 
- Guidelines to select/author links needs to be fixed (follow it based on closure on #1)
- No sample of application code at all in any of these repos, https://github.com/Azure/actions-workflow-samples/tree/workflow-templates/workflow-templates/AppService
- Every template should have comments included so customers know what to change and modify.

@N-Usha  added some comments or thoughts ..

We also need to look at how we would like to promote it - if there is a possible keep the list small (may be just for AppService and Kubernetes) and include it Ignite news so you get a bit more visibility of this.

- Only those templates for which the .properties.json are included are only shown in the UX. We could potentially scope the experience to only the selected list of templates by not including the .properties.json for the rest of the templates.  

- Its always a flat list and the folder structure in the repo dint influence the way the templates show up in the UX. IMO there should have been a filter or search capability on the UX . will check with platform team on this feature ask.

-  I am fine with the repo name change as well.. Hierarchy change or the repo name change would only break all the existing URLs and need fixing.. we could fix both together if we need to take this change. But any specific reason why 'templates' is a better name? Do you think it has a better brand recall? Also https://github.com/Azure/actions-workflow-templates repo name is already taken and is getting used by all the integration experiences and we may need to find a new name.

- This is how the experience shows up when there are more than 6 custom templates and then has a button to shows more templates.  https://github.com/bcstestit/.github/actions/new (@gopinathch - You can play around in this test repo.. Let me know if U don't have access)

title: Azure Portal - Deployment Center AKS - ARC
Telemetry analysis: GitHub Actions

comments.body:
## Objective - Understand the depth & breadth of customer engagement with Azure, using GitHub Actions as a pivot - Build a methodical reasoning to identify action items to further enhance the engagement in a measurable way ## Scope - **Organization** | **Individual** It's not a choice between the two but really a prioritization call. Our hypothesis based on the initial analysis shows that Organization provides a more representative and discrete cohort which is also accessible for qualitative feedback. These reasons make it an obvious choice as a starting point. - **Active** | **Engaged** | **Highly Engaged** GitHub extended the Core 4 metrics with 6 new additions to include some organization specific measures like active, engaged and highly engaged organizations [MAO, MEO & MHEO](https://team.githubapp.com/posts/33976). These metrics provide a natural pivot for alignment since we are exploring a subset of this data. Our analysis shows that deriving any actionable insights for active individual or accounts is hard due to statistically insignificant data. Also with leadership interest on the engaged and dedicated accounts, our current focus is Engaged & Highly Engaged Organizations. - **Adoption** | **Engagement** | **Churn** Since we are using GitHub Actions as a lens for our analysis, Engagement and Churn are the factors that we can influence more prominently compared to Adoption. Our assumption is that by the time Actions is used, the choice of cloud infrastructure has already been made in majority of the cases. ## Framework For all the exploration we use a simple framework to baseline current state, build a methodical reasoning & identify relevant action items - What is the current state (Engagement & Churn)? - What is the reasoning behind the current state (Engagement & Churn)? - What actions should be taken? ## Approach We have created 3 broad categories for our analysis 1. **Breadth**: A measure of the footprint deploying to Azure or other clouds e.g. #repositories. Each repository is a potential candidate for deployment. Larger number of repositories mean more breadth. 2. **Depth**: A measure of the penetration within a candidate that is already deploying to Azure or other clouds e.g. #deployments. Each repository that is deploying can do more e.g. move from active to engaged, engaged to highly engaged etc. 3. **Revenue**: A measure of the contribution to ACR and ARR | Categories | |. | | :----------- | :------- | :--------- | | Breadth (eng, churn) | Depth (eng, churn) | Revenue (eng, churn) | |
  • - [ ] # repos
  • - [ ] # action types
  • - [ ] # languages
  • - [ ] more...
|
  • - [ ] # jobs
  • - [ ] # commits or PR(s)
  • - [ ] # avg. contributors
  • - [ ] # activity days
  • - [ ] more...
|
  • - [ ] # acr
  • - [ ] # arr
  • - [ ] more...
|

Looks good to me.

Feedback from leadership is focus a bit more on engaged and highly engaged and then think about:
- How it is across clouds?
- How the language/framework split between them?
- How individual/organizations?
- How the churn in these categories for Azure and other clouds?
